Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] chi square tests are used to determine if there is any difference between the observed experimental values and the expected theoretical values. It can be used to check whether deviation from expected frequencies is larger than expected by chance or by error. If the deviation is larger, then you could try to determine which of the Hardy-Weinberg assumptions is being violated. This would be important to use to come up with the correct frequencies.
explainConcepts[SQ002] You can determine the frequency of alleles and genotypes by sex linked genes by using the equation p2+2pq+q2=1 for females and p+q=1 for males. the male equations gives you the phenotype and the allele frequency. If you know the frequency of recessives (q2), you can determine the frequency of dominant and heterozygous by using the two equations. therefore, determining allele frequency and genotypes using sex linked genes is simple by applying the hardy-weinburg equation.
explainConcepts[SQ003] In generalized transduction, a large number of bacterial genes are transferred. Bacterial DNA is packed into phage particles and transferred to the host cell. In Special sized transaction, only a few bacterial genes are transferred and strain-specific genes are transducer instead of a wide variety of genes. in both, viruses may be used to transfer the genes because viruses are able to invade the host cell and then force the cell to replicated and produce it's genes. By doing this, the bacterial genes transferred will then be produced by the cell.
phenomenonA Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonA[comment] This topic interests be because I have a passion for medicine. Bacteria and viruses prove to cause challenges to us by invading our cells and causing complications by causing our cells to produce their, usually, harmful genes via these two processes. An example of specialized transaction is λ phages in Escherichia coli, which is temperature dependent. This shows an example of bacterial genes being altered via viruses.
phenomenonB Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonB[comment] This concept is important because there are many sex linked genes that get passed down to the next generation and it is important to know the frequencies of these in the populations and try to prevent passing those down. An example in real life would be hemophilia. The frequency of the hemophilia gene has changed over the years; however, you would be able to take the genotype for a person who has the recessive trait and then calculate the frequencies of the homozygous dominant and heterozygous/

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The chi square test is used to determine if one criterium of the five characteristics of the Hardy Weinberg equilibrium is being violated. Using the degree of freedom, x squared is calculated. If x squared is less than 0.05, then the hypothesis is rejected and the deviation is not due to chance.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Allele and genotype frequencies can be found for sex linked genes as well. The Hardy Weinberg equilibrium is used, but is different for males. Females use p squared + 2pq + q squared while males use p + q =1.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Transduction is a form of genetic recombination using viruses. In generalized transduction, only bacterial DNA is added to the phage head and thus bacterial DNA is transferred to a new bacterium. In specialized transduction, only a few bacterial genes are transported along with the viral DNA, so the recipient cell only receives some bacterial genes.
phenomenonA Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonA[comment] Genetic recombination is the process that bacteria use to gain beneficial mutations like antibiotic resistance genes. Viruses, which usually harm bacteria, can actually help the bacteria by transferring DNA between them, which is interesting to me.
phenomenonB Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonB[comment] The equations for male versus female frequencies differs to show that females can be carriers of the gene and not show it. I like using these equations because it shows how males are more prone to getting recessive X-linked diseases.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Chi square tests ask whether an observed outcome fits an expected outcome. In the context of genotype frequencies in a population, the null hypothesis is that the genotypic frequencies are in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In men, population allele frequencies are the same as genotypic frequencies because men have a single X chromosome (no homologue).
explainConcepts[SQ003] Generalized transduction involves infection of a bacterium with a virus, fragmentation of the bacterial chromosome and the reformation of the viral heads but some heads form around a piece of the bacterial DNA which can now be transferred to a new bacterium by infection and incorporated by recombination. Specialized transduction occurs when a prophage such as lambda excises incorrectly and the excision includes a piece of the bacterial chromosome.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] In a chi square test you figure out the (observe-expected)^2 / expected. After this is found, one compares the value with the degrees of freedom in mind to the value on the chi square chart. This is then compared to the value of 0.05. If it is greater than 0.05, we reject the hypothesis. If the it is less than 0.05, we accept the hypothesis. When dealing with Hardy Weinberg, our hypothesis is that the populaiton is at Hardy Weinberg equilibrium. If we reject this hypothesis, we know that one of the Hardy Weinberg assumptions has been broken, so mutation, selection, migration, a small population, or non-random mating has occurred.
explainConcepts[SQ002] For males, most genes are found on X chromosomes. As a result, their allele frequency (p or q) is equal to their genotype. However, females allele frequency (p or q) is not equal to their genotype. Their genotype is equal to p^2, 2pq, or q^2.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Generalized transduction occurs when bacterial DNA is packaged into phage particles and transferred to the host. It is then used in chromosomal mapping. This transfers a large number of bacterial genes. Specialized transduction occurs in strain-specific genes. This transfers few bacterial genes.
phenomenonA The chi square test can be used to detect whether allele frequencies in populations are inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions
phenomenonA[comment] If a mutation of fur color occurs within a population, the expected frequencies based on the Hardy Weinberg equilibrium will be different than the observed frequencies.
phenomenonB Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonB[comment] In recessive sex linked genes, the frequency of recessive genes (q) reperesents the frequency of recessive genes found on males. Hemophilia and color-blindness is an example of sex-linked recessive genes.

groupTime425 97.38

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] In general, chi square analysis is used to compare expected values and observed values. This is done in order to determine the likelihood that the observed values are due to chance. When this likelihood is low, then the values are considered statistically valid. In this particular example, the allele frequency predictions from the Hardy-Weinberg equation are the "expected" values. The observed values are compared to these predictions, and a chi square test can be used to determine how statistically valid the observed values are.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Because males and females have different sex chromosomes, calculating the frequency of alleles of sex linked genes is different than autosomal genes. When calculating the frequency in female humans, you use the standard p2+2pq+q2=1 formula. This is because females have two X-chromosomes. However, in males, who have only one X chromosome, the formula is simplified to p+q=1. Therefore, it is crucial to consider which half of the population you are measuring.
explainConcepts[SQ003] When viruses invade a cell, they overtake the DNA replication process and begin copying their own (viral) DNA. This extra viral DNA is then repackaged into new viruses and expelled from the cell. However, sometimes during this repackaging phase of viral infection, the new viruses pick up bacterial DNA. They can then carry this bacterial DNA from one bacterial cell to another, where it can be integrated into a new bacteria's DNA.
phenomenonA The chi square test can be used to detect whether allele frequencies in populations are inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions
phenomenonA[comment] This is the second time the chi square test has come up in this course. Last time it was in reference to determining patters of inheritance.
phenomenonB Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonB[comment] Viruses can be used to laboratories to intentionally pass genes from one cell to another, or even from one organism to another. The application of this knowledge is incredibly wide and diverse in the field of scientific research.
groupTime426 2540.37

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that chi square analysis is used to compare expected values and observed values. This is done in order to determine the likelihood that the observed values are due to chance. I understand that this is crucial in scientific reporting, and that all present day studies use the chi square test (although they normally just report the p value, and do not waste time reporting the whole test itself). When this the p value is low, then the values are considered statistically valid. I understand that in most fields of science, the standard accepted p value is 0.05. In this particular example, the allele frequency predictions from the Hardy-Weinberg equation are the "expected" values. The observed values are compared to these predictions, and a chi square test can be used to determine how statistically valid the observed values are. I understand the implications that frequencies that do not match Hardy Weinberg predictions represent populations that are evolving in ways that break the Hardy Weinberg assumptions.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that males and females have different sex chromosomes, and therefore calculating the frequency of alleles of sex linked genes is different than autosomal genes. When calculating the frequency in female humans, you use the standard p2+2pq+q2=1 formula. This is because females have two X-chromosomes. However, in males, who have only one X chromosome, the formula is simplified to p+q=1. Therefore, it is crucial to consider which half of the population you are measuring.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand that when viruses invade a cell, they overtake the DNA replication process and begin copying their own (viral) DNA. I understand that this extra viral DNA is then repackaged into new viruses and expelled from the cell, with the intent of moving onto a new cell and beginning the process all over again. However, sometimes during this repackaging phase of viral infection, the new viruses pick up bacterial DNA. They can then carry this bacterial DNA from one bacterial cell to another, where it can be integrated into a new bacteria's DNA. As long as the virus does not lyse the second bacterium, then it will go on to reproduce through asexual reproduction and further proliferate the hybrid DNA.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that HFR bacterium have a high rate of recombination with other bacteria. I understand that the DNA is moved from one cell to another in an chronological manner. By interrupting the conjugation at various time intervals and then applying an antibiotic to kill the donor HFR cells, geneticists can observe the phenotypes of the remaining cells and create a time map of the genes that transferred from the HFR bacterium to the F- bacterium. This gives solid evidence of the order in which the genes are positioned on the plasmid. I find this to be a very logical process, although it appears extremely difficult at first.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Chi square analysis evaluates the influence of chance on genetic data. Outcomes of independent assortment and fertilization are subject to random fluctuations from their predicted occurrences as a result of deviation. Hardy Weinberg is contingent upon 5 factors: no mutation, large population, random mating, no migration, and no genetic drift. Chi square test can be used to determine whether or not a population meets these terms.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In species where sex is chromosomally determined, females have two X chromosomes while males only have one. In females, gene frequencies are the same as for any other locus. In males, frequencies of the genotypes are the same as frequencies to the alleles in the population. Males = p + q and Females= p^2 +2pq + q^2. One can use the Hardy Weinberg Law to determine the frequencies of the alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Generalized transduction is when bacterial DNA instead of phage is packed into phage particles and transferred to host. Generalized transduction can transfer a large number of bacterial genes. It is used in linkage and chromosomal mapping. Specialized transduction involves strain-specific genes that are transduced and transfers few bacterial genes.
phenomenonA The chi square test can be used to detect whether allele frequencies in populations are inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions
phenomenonA[comment] I have taken several biology courses and in every lab I have taken chi square test has been taking into consideration on whether to reject or accept the null hypothesis. I find this interesting how it can be applied to both genetics and other science courses.
phenomenonB Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonB[comment] Cystic Fibrosis affects approximately 1 in 2,000 individuals of European decent. Using the Hardy Weinberg equations, one can calculate the frequency and genotype of cystic fibrosis in a population. I find this interesting since we have been learning about cystic fibrosis in discussion.
groupTime426 1500.15

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that chi square tests can be used to detect whether allele frequencies meet the 5 contingent factors it is based upon. One can take a chi square test by comparing the expected and observed ratio of offspring with their certain classes. In order to get chi square, it is (observed-expected)^2/expected. To get the degree of freedom, one subtracts one from the classes. Using these numbers one can either reject or accept the null hypothesis.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Hardy Weinberg equations can be used to determine the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes. This can be done by using the equations p + q = 1 and p^2 +2pq + q^2. Males represent the first formula and females represent the second in latter. p stands for the frequency of 1 allele and q stands for the frequency of another allele in a population. p^2 represents individuals who are homozygous for allele 1, q^2 represents individuals who are homozygous for allele 2, and 2pq represents individuals who are heterozygotes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Generalized transduction is random and specialized transduction involves specific DNA fragments. Generalized transduction is mediated lytic phages where any DNA segment can be transferred by the virus and not integrate the segment of bacterial chromosome. Specialized transduction is mediated by lysogenic phages where the DNA fragments get integrated into the bacterial chromosome.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] To my understanding, HFR (high-frequency recombination) bacterium is a special class of F cells that donates genetic information to F cells. Bacterial genes may be mapped to chromosomes by conjugation between HFR bacterium and F- bacterium by looking at the plasmid conducted and the new bacterial DNA. I am still a little confused on this topic.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] If the deviation from the frequencies are different than what is expected by chance, then researchers study which of the Hardy-Weinberg assumptions (no migration, no mutation, random mating, infinite population, and no selection) are being violated. This is done by calculating the allele frequencies from the genotype frequencies then using the allele frequencies in the parental generation to predict the genotype frequencies of the offspring. If the frequencies are not relatively close to the frequencies observed in the parental generation, then there is evidence that Hardy-Weinberg is being violated, and chi square can be performed.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Since females have 2 X chromosomes, gene frequencies are the same for any other locus. Since males only have one X chromosome, genotype frequencies are the same as the allele frequencies in the population. Males: p+q=1 Females: p^2+2pq+q^2
explainConcepts[SQ003] Transduction is when a virus replicates bacterial DNA from one bacterium to another through viral replication cycles. Generalized transduction is when instead of a phage, bacterial DNA is packaged into phage particles and transferred to the host. This transfers a large amount of bacterial genes. In specialized transduction, transfer of bacterial DNA is not random and only strain-specific genes are transduced. This type of transduction only transfers a few bacterial genes.
phenomenonA Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonA[comment] Hemophilia is a sex-linked disorder, and it can be caused by different factors which have different frequencies in males and females.
phenomenonB Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonB[comment] Generalized transduction is random and transfers many bacterial genes, while specialized transduction transfers very few bacterial genes.

knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand that since females have 2 x chromosomes, they're allelic frequencies are the same at either locus. explainConcepts[SQ001] If the chi square test produces results inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions, it signifies that the population did not adhere by one or more of the following Hardy Weinberg stipulations: a large population, random mating, lack of mutation, and equal survival and reproduction rates. This variance occurs because the population may be affected by one or more possible factors, including mutation, genetic drift, gene flow, or natural selection.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes can be determined using a variance on the Hardy Weinberg equilibrium equation. For females (XX), the p^2 + 2pq + q^2 = 1 equation can still be used. For males (XY), however, only p + q = 1 can be used.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Lytic phages mediate generalized transduction, in which the virus' DNA takes over and destroys the cell. Lysogenic phages mediate specialized transduction, in which the virus' DNA merges with the cell's existing DNA.

groupTime426 285.28

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Through this analysis. we can look at the population as a whole and determine if evolution is occurring. If it is, then one or more of the HW assumptions must be being violated. If no evolution is occurring, then all assumptions are met.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] This is using the 2 HW equations for evolution. To determine male's frequencies you use p + q = 1. To determine the female's frequencies you use p^2 + 2pq + q^2 = 1. These equations will give you the frequency of a normal individual, a female carrier, or an affected individual.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Through transduction, a bacteriophage will inject new DNA into a host cell. The host cell will then incorporate that DNA into its chromosome. The cell will then enter the lytic or lysogenic cycle. Thus, genetic recombination occurs.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] We know that Hardy Weinberg equilibrium represents a population that hasn't undergone any type of selection. This population must also be large enough to sample its data and other factors can't affect it, i.e., migration, mutations, gene flow, genetic drift. When we apply the chi square test, we are able to observe the expected population and it's gene frequencies and compare this data against what is observed. This ratio can help us determine if the factors that deter Hardy Weinberg equilibrium exist in this population.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Sex linked genes exist on sex determining chromosomes, and, while only comprising 2 chromosomes out of the 23 pairs in humans, these chromosomes also contain genes that don't define the sex of an individual. We know that color blindness is an x linked recessive trait. Since women have two x linked genes, the likelihood of her being homozygous for this recessive gene is significantly low. Men, only having one x chromosome, have a much higher risk of being colorblind. We can also apply binomial theorem to sex linked traits. p^2 + 2pq +q^2 = 1; this equation represents the ratio of individuals in a population and the variables are their genes, e.g., p is allele A, and q is allele a. Since men have only one x chromosome, we can use the square root of this equation, and the q frequency will actually represent their frequency of either the dominant or recessive x chromosome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Bacteria have a long history of mutating or developing resistance to antibiotics. One way of achieving this differentiation is to receive chromosomes from an outside source. When a bacteria receives chromosomes from a bacteriophage, we call this process transduction. Generalized transduction results when a bacteriophage directly injects its prophage into the host cell and the cell takes up this material into its genetic code. Specialized transduction is when a bacteria already has a prophage in its genetic code, and this prophage gets transferred to another bacteria. We see this during the lysogenic cycle.
phenomenonA Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonA[comment] I believe the more we are able to understand transduction and genetics, we can master the process of gene manipulation and engineer organisms to do an endless scope of functions.
phenomenonB Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonB[comment] It's very fascinating that every human has the genetic code to be either sex, yet males are a result of a tiny y chromosome. The shows that they have all the genes needed to be women but factors in the y chromosome result in a different sex.
groupTime426 1572.26

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] Hardy Weinberg equilibrium is a representation of genetic frequencies in a population using binomial theorem. If there is deviation from what is expected in the population, we know there are factors in play (selection for example) altering our data.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Men have only one x chromosome and a y chromosome. Women have two x chromosomes. This means women have a lower chance of resulting in an undesirable x linked recessive phenotype. We also know that if p+q=1, where p is the frequency say chromosome X and q is the frequency of chromosome x, then we can determine the number of men with either x or X chromosome, yet would still have to use p^2 +2pq + q^2 = 1 to determine the frequency of occurrence in women.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Bacteria receive genetic information from bacteriophages via transduction. Generalized transduction is direct reception of chromosomes from the phage and specialized transduction is when a bacteria passes on phage material to another bacteria.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] HFR bacteria have a high probability of recombination, and we use this high chance to cross DNA with recipient bacteria, marked F-, and the resulting frequency of this these genotypes allow us to map the genes.

groupTime425 73.21

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] When the results of a chi square test indicates that a population's allele frequency is inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions, then at least one of the following must be true: 1) The population is small, thus leading to genetic drift. 2) The population is not isolated, thus causing gene flow. 3) Mutation occurs, thus introducing new alleles into the population. 4) Natural selection occurs, thus expressing the more "fit" trait. 5) Non-random mating occurs, thus causing more expressions of recessive phenotypes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The phenotypic expression frequency of certain sex-linked genes can be predicted due to whether the gene is located on the X chromosome or the Y chromosome. Traits can be either X-linked dominant, X-linked recessive, or Y-linked. If a mother with a X-linked dominant trait and a non-affected father mated, then 50% of her offspring would be affected with that trait. However, a father with a X-linked dominant trait passes this trait to all of his daughters. His sons do not receive this trait, because they inherit their father's Y chromosome.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Transduction is responsible for the diversity seen in bacteria. Generalized transduction is most common. This occurs when a phage inserts its viral DNA into a host cell. The viral DNA uses the host cell's cellular machinery to replicate its viral DNA, which is then packaged into virus capsules. A small percentage of that host cell's bacterial DNA are also packaged into capsules. This packaged bacterial DNA becomes the transducing phage. When a phage injects this DNA into a new host cell, part the DNA may be integrated into the bacterial chromosome via recombination. Specialized transduction occurs when a small part of the bacterial DNA remains attached to the phage DNA when transduction occurs. A piece of the phage DNA is left attached to the bacterial chromosome.
phenomenonA The chi square test can be used to detect whether allele frequencies in populations are inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions
phenomenonA[comment] The Hardy Weinberg equilibrium equation helps predict and track the genotypic frequencies from one generation to the next.
phenomenonB Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonB[comment] Transduction is one of the mechanisms responsible for the diversity within bacteria. Studying transduction in bacteria can help us better understand how they evolve and interact on a molecular level.
groupTime426 9431.05

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I know that the chi square test is used to analyze the significance of the results produced by the Hardy Weinberg equilibrium equation. The Hardy Weinberg criteria are as follows: 1) No mutation 2) No natural selection 3) Population must be infinitely big 4) Population must be isolated (No gene flow) 5) Random mating must occur.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand how certain sex linked traits are inherited from one generation to the next. The offspring of a mother with a X-linked dominant trait has a 50% chance of inheriting that trait. All female offsprings inherit their father's X-linked dominant trait. However the males do not inherit this trait from their father, since they receive their father's Y chromosome.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I know that transduction is a source of bacterial diversity. Specialized transduction occurs when a set of bacterial genes are transferred with a phage DNA into a new cell. The transferred set of bacterial genes are then transduced within the new cell.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand that by observing the plasmid transfer between HFR and F- bacterium, we can map the location of certain genes on the bacterial chromosome by using a technique known as interrupted mating.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Chi square analysis mathematically calculates how well a null hypothesis fits the numerical results. The Hardy Weinburg equation provides data for the alleles in a population that is not evolving. Performing a chi square test can tell researchers how far a population deviates from the ideal population. A large deviation indicates that the population encounters mutation, migration, natural selection, mating is non-random, and the population size is not infinite.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Because males are heterogametic, the number of males in a population that express an x-linked trait will be equal to the frequency of x-linked alleles in the population. Because females are homogametic, q^2 in the Hardy-Weinburg equation will calculate the number of females homozygous for a specific x-linked allele.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Transduction occurs when bacterial DNA is transported by a bacteriophage. In generalized transduction, a large number of randomly selected bacterial genes are transported to a different host bacterium. Specialized transduction is the transfer of a small number of genes that are specific for one strain of bacteria. Both types of transduction produce genetic diversity in the population.
phenomenonA Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonA[comment] Generalized and specialized transduction, as well as other modes of creating genetic diversity in bacterial populations, can be helpful when studying antibiotic resistance. As a future healthcare provider, understanding antibiotic resistance and its implications is very important.
phenomenonB The chi square test can be used to detect whether allele frequencies in populations are inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions
phenomenonB[comment] A large deviation indicates that Hardy-Weinburg assumptions have been violated, and investigating which assumption has been violated could possibly be answered by social events in a population, such as a high percentage of refugees seeking asylum in a relatively homogenous country.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The chi square test uses statistical analysis to determine if populations are evolving, or do not meet Hardy-Weinberg assumptions. The degrees of freedom is matched with the probability value for that set of conditions. The degrees of freedom is the number of classes minus one. If the p-value is less than 0.05, then the null hypothesis is rejected and H-W conditions are not met.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Sex linked genes are different from autosomal genes. Sex linked genes are either on the X or Y chromosome. Males get XY and Females get XX. Sex linked genes are usually on the X chromosome because most of the Y chromosome is not expressed. Males are at a higher risk of receiving sex linked genetic diseases because they only receive one X.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Generalized transduction happens when random fragments of bacterial DNA is packaged along with the bacteriophage head and then recombined. Specialized transduction occurs when the repackaged bacteria DNA is not random, but strain specific. A larger number of bacterial genes are transfered in generalized than specialized transduction.
phenomenonA Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonA[comment] Transduction can be used to map the genes of the bacteria. If the genes are located closely to each, or are linked, then they can both be transduced in a process called cotransduction.
phenomenonB The chi square test can be used to detect whether allele frequencies in populations are inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions
phenomenonB[comment] Results from the chi square test can be used to understand what conditions are violated and how the population is evolving.

explainConcepts[SQ002] We can determine allele/genotype/phenotype frequencies of sex linked genes, and diseases cause by them, using the equation p^2 + 2pq + q^2 according to Hardy Weinberg equilibrium. Because of this, if we have the frequency of q in the male, it is also the frequency of q^2 (and the same for p & p^2).

explainConcepts[SQ001] In order for allel frequencies to follow Hardy Weinberg predictions there has to be no mutation, no selection, random mating, infinte population size, and no migration or gene flow. Thus, if all of this is followed then the results can be predicted. However, even if a single thing changes there could be different results. Therefore, Chi square test- a statistical method for calculating the goodness of fit between observed value and expected value. The chi square test can be used to calculate data, is the variation in data due to chance or is it due to one of the variables that we are testing. Then based on the critical value and degree of freedom, one can determine weather the data is due to chance or due to variables. As well as they can determine weather the data is consistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions.
explainConcepts[SQ002] We can calculate the frequency of alleles and genotype for a sex linked gene/traits in Hardy Weingberg population. In humans, the female is XX and male is XY, the frequency of x linked alleles and the frequency of male expressing those x linked traits would be same. This is because each male has only one x chromosome and thus an male receiving x chromosome would be equal to the genotype and allele frequency in population. For example, color blindness is female is 1/1250 =0.0008. q2=0.0008 and q= 1/34. It means 1/34 women have colorblindness. Note: P is dominant allel and q is recessive allele. In male the formula p+q and for female p2+2pq+q2 is used to determine the sex linked frequency.
explainConcepts[SQ003] In generalized transduction, a small segment of DNA is carried from the bacterium by a bacteriophage or virus and then inserted in another bacterium. After this happen, an enzyme is produced that breaks down the host DNA into smaller fragments. Then phage DNA is replicated and coat and phage proteins are produced. During formation of the phage few of the phage cell have bacterial DNA instead of the phage DNA and then they are carried to other bacterium causing little genetic diversity. Specialized transduction involves the transfer of only specific genes using the phage form one bacteria to another. The lambda phage, that infects E. coli is a good example. in doing this, some part of the phage DNA is left in bacteria and some of the bacterial DNA is taken away with phage DNA. this is rare though. However, due to this when the phage infects other bacteria the older bacteria's DNA is transfer to it and thus causes genetic variation.

phenomenonA[comment] It can be used to study in linkage and chromosomal mapping. We can study the affects of this new specific genes on the bacteria, its advantages and disadvantages for future generation.
phenomenonB Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonB[comment] Due to transduction there can be increased genetic diversity. Therefore, if there is some disease or some factor that kills all the similar bacteria that have little gentic diversity would survive. For example, they might be producing some byproduct due to change in their genes that could provide them immunity agains the foreign particle. Moreover, that by products can be used by humans to cure diseases. An example of this is using the penicillin vaccine which was created from the bacterial by product.

groupTime425 23.33

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The chi square test is an important statistical tool that is crucial to determining if results are statistically significant. The prevalence of certain alleles can be calculated for specific populations, according to the Hardy Weinberg principle. A practical use of the Hardy Weinberg principle is that it allows us to make predictions about allele frequencies in populations. The chi square test allows us to compare predicted allele frequencies with observed allele frequencies in a population. This is important because predicted patterns based probability need a way to be "tested" and verified as meaningful.
explainConcepts[SQ002] With sex linked genes, such as X-linked genes, we use a slightly modified equation in evaluating the allele frequencies and genotype frequencies via the Hardy Weinberg principle. If an allele is X-linked, then a female will have twice the number of alleles or copies of the gene than males in the population since males only have one copy of the X-chromosome. By doubling the allele frequency for females, we can account for this discrepancy. As far as genotype frequencies, males are hemizygous since they only have one copy of the X chromosome with no corresponding homolog. While females in the population will still be homozygous or heterozygous, the hemizygous males will have only one allele (no combination) of the X-linked gene.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Transduction describes the transfer of bacterial genetic material from one bacterium to another via viruses. When a virus leaves a cell that it was previously infecting, it can sometimes take some of the genetic material from the bacteria along with it, incorporated into its own viral genome. When the virus goes on to infect another bacterium, it inserts its viral genome as before, but now that viral genome also contains genetic material from the previous bacterium that will also be transferred. Generalized transduction refers to situations where the bacterial genetic material is floating in the cytoplasm, and all the genes have the same random probability that they will be incorporated into the phage head. The chance that certain bacterial DNA will be recombined through transduction via the virus is random. Specialized transduction refers to situations where only strain specific genes are transduced via the virus to the bacterium, meaning this type of transduction of DNA is not random.
phenomenonA Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonA[comment] In discussion we’ve focused on studying the components of cystic fibrosis. While cystic fibrosis is not a sex-linked gene, we have seen the implications and usefulness of determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes. Especially in situations where the allele in question is a mutated allele that results in disease or loss of function in the body, being able to determine frequencies in given populations is helpful in both making predictions and determining possible reasons behind the relative increase or decrease in allele frequency in a population. While this is important with cystic fibrosis, it would be even more important for sex-linked genes such as X-linked genes because males are hemizygous for the X chromosome and express even recessive X-linked disease with just one copy.
phenomenonB Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonB[comment] Understanding the mechanisms behind transduction is important and interesting to me because I’ve always been interested in how viruses function and why they are so different than bacteria. In addition, bacterial gene exchange and recombination is also related to anti-biotic resistance, which is an important issue that is currently growing in severity.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I feel very comfortable in my understanding of both the Hardy-Weinberg principle, which is something we’ve talked about multiple times in both class, as well as the chi square test, which has been discussed both in this course and in my previous courses. Because the Hardy Weinberg principle allows us to make predictions about allele frequencies and genotype frequencies in populations, I understand that we need a model or method of determining whether or not and discrepancies between these predictions and actual frequencies in a population are statistically significant. As with all the results of empirical research, there must be an operationalized, working definition of what constitutes “significant” or when data can be considered influential when compared to controls or baselines. The chi square test helps to make the term "significance" a quantifiable measure rather than a subjective judgment call of a given researcher or analyst.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] I understand the significance of being able to determine and subsequently predict allele frequencies and genotype frequencies, especially for X-linked genes, since males are hemizygous for the X chromosome and therefore have a much greater chance of increased penetrance and expressivity of deleterious mutations found on the X chromosome. While I understand this concept, I don’t feel fully comfortable with the specifics of how to calculate the frequencies for sex-linked genes. I hope that further discussion and practice problems will be able to give me a more functional understanding of this concept.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] I understand the overall mechanism and concept of transduction, when recombination occurs via the transfer of bacterial genetic information from one bacteria to the next via incorporation and subsequent transfer of the bacterial genes into the viral genes that are inserted when the virus infects the next cell. However, I don’t understand the specific process by which generalized transduction occurs. As covered in both the book and lecture, generalized transduction occurs when the bacterial genetic material is floating in the cytoplasm, and all the genes have the same random probability that they will be incorporated into the phage head. The book provided only a vague explanation of why or how this process is truly random, and I feel like there would have to be some sort of underlying pattern or preferred location in the bacteria that would result in a higher probability of transduction.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] I understand the importance of HFR bacterium in constructing genetic maps of bacterial chromosomes. To start of with, HFR bacteria are always donors, they are a special class of F+ cells, and they result from the spontaneous integration of the F factor (fertility factor) plasmid into their chromosome. HFR stands for high frequency of recombination, and by using a technique called the interrupted matings technique, specific genes can be identified based on the time it takes them to undergo recombination. Experiments that utilized the interrupted mating technique led to the discovery that the E. coli linkage map is circular. This is a crucial piece of information that can tell us a lot about the nature of bacterial DNA and chromosomes. Maps are constructed using time, as well as the fact that depending on the location that the fertility factor is integrated in the HFR chromosome, the temporal order of genes that recombine changes, but the actual order or relative position along the circular chromosome is always the same. Using different HFR strains in mapping experiments allows for many “timelines” to be observed and then reconstructed relative to each other, ultimately forming the circular bacterial gene map.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The chi square test is used to detect allele frequencies by comparing the probabilities of each allele occurring within a population. The chi square test can be inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg principles because Hardy Weinberg equilibrium states that there must not be any extraneous factors that influence the frequency of certain alleles within a population. As long as there are no other factors affecting the population, allele frequencies can be determined using chi square tests can be utilized by scientists to see how many people within a population will likely inherit particular genes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Sex linked genes are those that do not occur within the autosomal region of the chromosome, but they are strictly placed within the sex chromosome; however, the frequencies of these alleles and genotypes can be determined using probability and observing populations.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Transduction is the transfer of genetic material among cells that occurs through viruses within these cells. Bacterial exchange is an outcome of this process. Generalized transduction occurs simply, through a bacteriophage or a phage, through a segment of DNA. Furthermore, specialized transduction occurs in a more complex way, depending on where the phage is located within the chromosome.
phenomenonA Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonA[comment] The frequency of alleles and genotypes within sex linked genes is critical to determining how mutations occur within sex linked genes. For example, when people inherit extra X chromosomes and they have some behavioral alterations, scientists can determine how common these incidents are and attempt to limit the frequency within populations.
phenomenonB The chi square test can be used to detect whether allele frequencies in populations are inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions
phenomenonB[comment] Chi square tests can be used to determined the allele frequencies of many types of genes within populations; for example, if a chi square test is used to determine how many people have or could potentially have cystic fibrosis, scientists could utilize this information to determine the test's consistency with Hardy Weinberg principles to see if more or less people are obtaining the disease within certain regions throughout the world and we can come closer to determining a cause for this disease.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Chi square tests are vital in determining the validity of experiments. If observed allele frequencies in a population are different than what is expected in a Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium population, one can use a chi square test to determine what the probability is that the population is not in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes is the same as that of autosomal genes except with a slight variation. p^2 + 2pq + q^2 = 1 is used for X linked genes in women to find genotype frequencies, and p + q=1 is used to find allele frequencies. For males, only p+q+1 is used because males can only have a single X, so the allele frequency is the same as the genotype frequency.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Generalized transduction is associated with the lytic cycle of viral infection, where the viral DNA/RNA is used by the cell ribosomes to create more prophages and eventually destroying the cell. Specialized transduction is associated with the lysogenic cycle, where the virus injects its DNA into the bacterium, merging it with the bacterial DNA, ultimately not having much effect on the bacterial cell. Generalized transduction can exchange bacterial genes between bacteria, but usually they are lysed. Specialized transduction is much more likely to help exchange bacterial genes among other bacteria.
phenomenonA Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonA[comment] This obviously relates to viral infection and also bacterial infection. Bacteria can develop different strains that are resistant to antibiotics through this process.
phenomenonB Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonB[comment] This, like autosomal genes is very important in population genetics but also simply for a couple interested in their future child's probability of having a sex-linked disease.

groupTime425 178.86

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Using the chi square test allows a person to compare the observed allele frequencies in a population to the allele frequencies that were expected for the population. If the value yielded by the chi square test is greater than the value at the .05 probability level corresponding to the degrees of freedom for the population in consideration, then it can be inferred that the population is not consistent with the predictions. However, if the chi square value were less than the number taken from the table, then there is a good chance that the frequencies are consistent with the predictions.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes can be found by analyzing the offspring of a parental cross. If all males have the same phenotype for the gene, then it can be assumed that the mother if homozygous for an allele. If the males have different phenotypes, then the mother is heterozygous. If all daughters produced have the same phenotype then it is likely that the father either has the same allele as a mother who is homozygous for the allele or has a recessive allele while the mother is homozygous dominant for the allele. However, if there are different phenotypes in the daughters then it can be assumed that the mother is heterozygous for the allele.
explainConcepts[SQ003] This takes place when phage DNA is injected into a cell, then proceeds to destroy the host DNA. Replication synthesis of phage DNA will occur and cause phage proteins to assemble. These phages will mature and then proceed to infect other cells and integrate bacterial DNA into the recipient chromosome. Generalized transduction occurs when the packaging of DNA fragements and the genes that are transduced is random. Most cases of this are abortive. Meanwhile, in specialized transduction the transfer of bacterial DNA is not random, but instead, only strain-specific genes are transduced.
phenomenonA Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonA[comment] The process of transduction was shown through the Lederberg-Zinder Experiment in which two auxotrophic strains of Salmonella were placed on opposite sides of a Davis U-tube and then tests were run to see if the prototrophs from each side would grow.
phenomenonB Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonB[comment] In the royal British family, there was a common trend of hemophilia in the 19th and 20th centuries. By determining the frequency of the alleles and genotypes of this sex linked gene the probability of royal offspring having the disease could have been determined.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] This is extremely important since it allows us to determine if the observed allele frequencies are in agreement with Hardy Weinberg equilibrium. If there is no difference between the two, we know that the population is is HW equilibrium. If, however, there is a measured difference we know that the population in not in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium and something must be influencing the observed deviation in the population (Ex natural selection, nonrandom mating etc)
explainConcepts[SQ002] Sex linked genes are unique because we can still use the HW equilibrium equation, but which part of the equation we use varies with males and females. For males (since they only have 1 X chromosome) the genotype frequency is equal to the allele frequency so we can use p+q=1. In females (2 X chromosomes) the genotype frequency is the same as the autosomal genes so we can use P2+3pq+q2=1
explainConcepts[SQ003] General transduction is a broader category and it is random which bacterial genes are picked up by the virus. Specialized transduction is a more specific category and occurs when specific genes are transduced (NOT random). Both of these methods of transduction provide a way for bacteria to obtain new genes (and increase genetic variation) through virus mediated gene exchange.
phenomenonA Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonA[comment] bacterial gene exchange via transduction is extremely important in the health care field as it is currently being used in bone marrow stem cell research.
phenomenonB Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonB[comment] For me, this is a fascinating concept because it allows us to calculate theoretical gene and genotype frequencies if a population is in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium. This related to sex linked genes as males and females will have different allele frequencies due to females having 2 X chromosomes and males only having 1.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The chi square test is a statistical test that determines if there is a significant differences between observed and expected values. This test can be used to compare observed allele frequencies with those frequencies that are predicted by the p^2 + 2pq + q^2 =1 equation, and therefore we can compare to see if the actual frequencies are close enough to the predicted for the population to be considered in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Since female humans have two copies of the X sex chromosome and males only have one, they have different ratios of allele frequencies for sex-linked genes. Therefore for males, the frequency of occurence of a genotype is the same as the frequency of alleles in the population.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Transduction is the process of DNA being transmitted from bacterium to bacterium by a viral mechanism. This can be generalized transduction, where the virus packages the bacterial genes in its head instead of the phage, which transmits a lot of information, or by specialized transduction, which is strain-specific and occurs if extra bacterial DNA is also included when the viral DNA is excised.
phenomenonA The chi square test can be used to detect whether allele frequencies in populations are inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions
phenomenonA[comment] If the chi square doesn't find significant difference and the population is in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium, this is interesting because that equilibrium is an ideal and rarely occurs in nature. An interesting example is blood type, since their is no natural selection for that trait in humans.
phenomenonB Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonB[comment] This is explains why it is much more common for men to be color blind, since it is an x-linked trait. Therefore males' allele frequency numbers express how many alleles in the population for color blindness.

These are two slightly separated processes that are two types of transduction. I did not fully understand this from the lecture, but once I read the powerpoint it made more sense to me, and the book did not explain the mechanism for specialized transduction, and went very in depth into generalized transducction.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] When an HFR bacterium conjugates with an F- bacterium and starts transmitting its F factor, the circular chromosome can go in two directions. Which direction it moves in determines the order of the genes, but even though conjugation could theoretically start at many points, there are only two directions it could move. So given many repetitions of this process, it becomes clear that certain genes always follow other genes, so if you know that a bacterial chromosome is circular, you can see which genes are next to each other.

explainConcepts[SQ001] A chi-squared test can be used to determine the amount of deviation of the observed frequences to the expected frequencies. A violation of the Hardy-Weinberg predictions can be assumed if deviation is larger than expected.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The Hardy-Weinberg law can be used to determine the frequency of sex-linked genes. If alleles are X-linked, then women can be homozygous or heterozygous, and their Hardy-Weinberg frequencies would be the same as their autosomal gene frequencies. Men only have one X gene, so their genotypical frequencies will be p and q.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Generalized transduction can be mediated by lytic viruses, which undergo transcription and translation. A lytic virus will infect a host cell so that the host cell replicated the viral DNA. Specialized transduction invloved in specific genes and invloces lysongenic viruses. These viruses will directly insert itself into a host cell and when the host cell replicates, so will the virus's DNA.
phenomenonA Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonA[comment] Generalized transduction viruses are better at mapping bacterial chromosomes.

groupTime425 48.66

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The Chi Square Analysis is a method used by various scientists to determine if a hypothesis and its results are statistically significant. The Chi Square Value is denoted by the letter 'X' and is equivalent to the square root of observed minus expected squared over the expected. This value and the degrees of freedom, which is normally the number of variables minus one, but in this case there is only one degree of freedom since only one value is unknown and that one value, if known, can be used to calculate the rest of the variables, are used together to determine if the value is below or above 0.05. If the values are above 0.05 then the experiment’s hypothesis is generally refuted due to the fact that the value is not statistically significant; However, it is highly likely to get a value above the 0.05 mark when discussing allele frequencies within a population so that variation can be used to determine which condition is being broken in order to “ensure the effects” of the Hardy- Weinberg Law. Thus, the Chi Square Test can be used to portray discrepancies within the Hardy- Weinberg Law and allows one to determine the cause of the said discrepancy.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The Hardy- Weinberg Formulas, p + q =1 and p2 + 2pq + q2 =1, can be used to determine the frequency of alleles and genotypes associated with sex-linked genes. The first equation is used to determine the frequency of either the dominant (p) or the recessive allele (q), whereas, the second equation is used to determine the frequency of homozygous dominant individuals, heterozygotes, and homozygous recessive individuals, respectively. However in the case of sex linked genes, the first equation is used specifically for males in the sense that in sex linked genes, males can either have the disorder or not have it due to the fact that males have only one X chromosome. Females on the other hand have two X chromosomes, so the second equation corresponds to the frequency of homozygous dominant individuals, carriers, and homozygous recessive individuals. This application of the Hardy Weinberg formulas right fully depicts the fact that males are more susceptible to sex-linked disorders than females.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Transduction is a process in which viruses such as a bacteriophage carry bacterial DNA to another bacterium as the bacteriophage inserts its viral DNA components into the bacterium. This insertion of the viral DNA becomes incorporated into the bacteria’s genome and sometimes a piece of the bacterial chromosome is detached along with the viral DNA before the lysis of the bacterial cell to allow the manufacturing of the viral parts. Once that infected cell lyses, the new viral cells carry their DNA and the bacterial DNA to infect other bacterium. Through this process, viruses, in a way, allow the transfer of bacterial genes to the other bacteria. In specialized transduction, only certain specified genes of the bacterial DNA are transduced; whereas, generalized transduction deals with the random bacterial genes that are transduced by the assistance of viruses.
phenomenonA Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonA[comment] I find it interesting that the Hardy-Weinberg equations can be utilized to determine the frequency of sex-linked genes within males and females along with its original use to determine the frequency of autosomal genes and the frequency of the genotypes associated with those genes. This application is intriguing since the same two equations are used, but with different methods. The first equation directly correlates to the case in sex linked genes in the male population since males only have one X chromosome which determines if the individual will have the said disorder; whereas, since females have two X chromosomes, which are helpful in the situation of a recessive disease, they can be carriers of the disease thus the second equation is more befitting. I find it fascinating that such a link between sex linked genes and the Hardy Weinberg Equation is even possible. This connection was confusing initially, but after I understood how this could be applied, I understood the importance of such a tool.
phenomenonB The chi square test can be used to detect whether allele frequencies in populations are inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions
phenomenonB[comment] The chi square analysis is a scientific, mathematical tool that is used to determine the significance of the results observed in relation to the hypothesis tested. This chart shows that any value below the 0.05 mark is statistically significant and the hypothesis is supported by the results. In this case, it is expected for the results to be above the value of 0.05 if it is conducted in the real world rather than a lab simulation. This expectation can enable researchers to determine the cause of this high value in relation to the stipulations or conditions created by the Hardy Weinberg Law. For instance in a large population where there is a high immigration rate, scientists can use that Chi Square Test to determine if the high immigration rate is the cause that allele frequencies do not remain constant from generation to generation. A value greater than 0.05 does not necessarily correlate to the fact that the high immigration rate is the cause of allele frequency fluctuations amongst generations of that population, it is just an indication that one of the conditions required in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium is being broken. (It is up to the researcher to determine the cause of this high value.) I find it interesting how this mathematical model can be applied to general populations and the allele frequencies within that population.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand how a chi square analysis can be done to determine if a population fits or defies Hardy Weinberg Equilibrium. If this refuted, then one can infer that one of the conditions associated wit Hardy Weinberg Equilibrium is broken. If the value obtained using the chart and the degrees of freedom (which is 1 in this case) is greater than 0.05, then one can infer that either a mutation has occurred, selection has occurred, immigration and emigration has occurred, nonrandom mating has occurred to a large extent, and/or the population is not infinitely large. All of these situations are highly likely within a real population thus implying that the majority of the time the results reviewed are not statistically significant since the conditions required for Hardy Weinberg Equilibrium are simply ideal and not realistic. I also understand how this information can be applied to see which condition is being violated within a population. In this process, a virus injects its DNA into its host cell (the bacterial cell) and that DNA incorporates into the bacterial DNA and can activate the production of viral parts to create more viruses. At times, a portion of the bacterial DNA is connected to the viral DNA and can break off from the rest of the bacterial DNA, thus that bacterial DNA becomes placed within the viral parts (protein head and legs). Specialized transduction is related to only specific bacterial sequences whereas generalized transduction corresponds to random bacterial DNA being transduced. Furthermore, I understand that when a HFR bacteria mates with a F- bacterial cell, the F- remains F- since the F factor is transferred last and usually the sex pili breaks before the F factor can be transferred.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The chi square test can show whether the changes in allele frequency are by chance (the null hypothesis) or whether the deviations are statistically significant and a result of some force that is selecting for certain genotypes.
explainConcepts[SQ002] For X-linked alleles in females, Hardy-Weinberg frequencies are still calculated normally. In males, X-linked alleles are calculated by looking at only the p and the q alleles because males only have 1 allele for the gene.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Generalized transduction is by which any bacterial gene may be transferred to another bacterium via a bacteriophage, and typically carries only bacterial DNA and no viral DNA. Specialized transduction is the process by which genes that are near the bacteriophage genome may be transferred to another bacterium via a bacteriophage. The genes that get transferred always depend on where the phage genome is located on the chromosome.

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] The Hardy-Weinberg equation can be used to predict the allele frequencies in a population throughout generations. Chi square tests are used to check whether the actual allele frequencies from a population are following these Hardy-Weinberg predictions. If the chi squared null hypothesis is rejected, researchers can look at what is going on in the population that could lead to changes in the predicted gene frequencies. They could find that genetic drift, gene flow, or natural selection are playing a role in the changes.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] The Hardy-Weinberg equation can still be used to determine and predict the frequencies of alleles for sex-linked genes. The equation must be used slightly differently though. For X-linked genes, females can be homozygous or heterozygous and the Hardy-Weinberg equation can be used normally. Males only carry a single allele though for X-linked genes. This means the frequencies of the genotypes will be either p or q for males. The frequency of an X-linked allele in males will be the same as the frequency of that allele in their mothers, where the frequency in females will be the average of that in the mothers and fathers.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Transduction is virally mediated bacterial recombination. Generalized transduction is the transfer of a gene from a bacterial host to a bacterial recipient in a process that is mediated by a bacteriophage. Generalized transduction is characterized by the random nature of DNA fragments and genes that are transduced where each fragment of the chromosome has a chance of being recombined. Specialized transduction is genetic transfer of specific host genes by phages and strain-specific genes are transduced. The DNA representing a temperate bacteriophage breaks out of the host chromosome and brings bacterial DNA on either end.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Some bacteria are designated as high frequency recombination, Hfr, because they show an increased level of recombination compared to F+ cells. F- bacteria do not contain the fertility plasmid. Unlike when crossing a F+ and F- cell, when a Hfr and a F- cells are crossed the F- cell will remain that way. Scientists also noticed that crossing HfrxF- showed recombination of certain genes more than others. That is because through an experiment called interrupted mating technique, it was shown that depending on the Hfr strain, certain genes are transferred and recombined sooner than others which lead to the knowledge that the chromosome of the Hfr was transferred linearly. The conjugation tube could break at random times showing which genes were transferred earliest and this was used to determine the order of genes on the bacterial chromosome. Bacterial chromosomes were shown to be circular by using this process.

explainConcepts[SQ001] Chi square analysis is used to determine the influence of chance on genetic data. If the statical test for chi square (x^2) shows the P value less than 0.05 while figuring out the data on the table provided suggests that chance is not the only reason for genetics variation in the population, there must be some violation of hardy Weindberg equilibrium that is causing the variation in the allele frequencies in the population. A chi-square test can be used to check whether deviation from expected frequencies is larger than expected by chance. If deviation is larger, it suggest that the violation has occurred which allows researcher to investigate on why assumption was violates: natural selection, non-random mating, genetic drift, gene flow, or mutation.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Frequency of alleles and genotypes for sex linked genes is that in hemizygous individual, only one allele is present for gene on sex chromosome, example XY in male of humans. Y lacks all the genes to homologous to X, which says that only X determines the genotype for the individual. p+q=1 is used for sex linked individual genotype ratio and for allele frequency as its only for one allele under hardy weindberg. compare to homozygous individual for sex linked example female in humans. In order to determine genotype of individual under hardy weindberg p^2+2pq+q^2=1 is used while for allele frequency p+q=1 is used.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Transduction is a way for bacteria to get genetic variation among there species as bacteria have less chance of variation than eukaryotes as they produce asexually compare to eukaryotes that produce sexually. In the process of Transduction, when virus infect the bacteria they have power to lyse the cell and produce a plaque (which is how the lysis is seen in lab). Virus can cause genetics diversity in many ways one is by generalized transduction, where bacteria DNA is packed into Viral protein coat, which can then infect another host, but as it not a virus it won't lyse the cell instead it will introduce genetics variation when recombination with new bacterial DNA will be occurred. Another way to cause variation is by specialized transduction in which infected virus DNA is integrates into chromosomal DNA of bacteria and while after some stress occur which will cause virus DNA to be separated it will pick up some of the bacterial DNA which can then infect another host and also introduce genetic variation when they recombine with chromosomal DNA.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] If allele frequencies in the population are different from the Hardy Weinberg predictions, you can use a chi square test to determine it that difference is due to chance or not. To calculate chi squared, you would use this equation: (observed-expected)^2/expected. If the chi squared value is improbably large according to the distribution chart, then you can reject the null hypothesis.
explainConcepts[SQ002] In females, they have two X chromosomes, so to determine the allele and genotype frequencies, you would use the standard Hardy Weinberg equations. Males only have one X chromosome, so you would use the equation for allele frequency to find genotype frequency as well (p+q=1).
explainConcepts[SQ003] In generalized transduction, bacterial DNA is made into phage particles and transferred to the viral host. It results in the transfer of a large amount of bacterial DNA. In specialized transduction, only genes specific to that strain of bacteria are transferred to the host. This results in much fewer bacterial DNA being transferred.
phenomenonA Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonA[comment] Colorblindness is an X-linked gene and it affects males more than females because they only have one X chromosome. For example, the allele frequency for males with colorblindness is (1/12) and the genotype frequency is the same. The genotype frequency for women with colorblindness is (1/144).
phenomenonB Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonB[comment] Bacteriophages in transduction can undergo gene mutation which can be transferred to host. These mutant alleles can have many effects such as making the bacteria UV or temperature sensitive or even resistant to antibiotics. Antibiotic-resistance in bacteria has become a major problem today and the medical community is constantly trying to create new antibiotics to keep up with the resistant strains.

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] I understand that you can use the HW equations to predict allele and genotype frequencies in a population. I know that most populations are not in HW equilibrium and their frequencies will differ from the HW predictions. In order to determine if these differences are do to chance or another reason, we can use a chi square test. The equation to find X^2 is (expected-observed)^2/expected. This number can then be compared to a distribution chart using the degrees of freedom from the sample. If the X^2 number is high, we can reject the null hypothesis that allele and gene frequencies are due to chance.

Women have two X chromosomes, so you would use the equation (p+q=1) to determine allele frequencies and (p^2+2pq+q^2) to determine genotype frequency.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The chi square test is a statistical test that can be used to determine inconsistencies of allele frequencies in populations. It can be used to tell if there is a statistically significant difference between expected frequencies and the actual frequencies of alleles within a population. This information can be used to reject or fail to reject the null hypothesis.
explainConcepts[SQ002] The process for determining the frequency of alleles for sex linked is different than that for non-sex linked genes. For example with x-chromosome linked genes, one has to take into account that females will have two alleles for the sex-linked genes will males will only have one.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Bacterial transduction is a source of genetic variation in bacterial populations. It is the process by which genetic information is transferred from one bacterium to another via a virus. General transduction is the process by which any bacterial gene is transferred to another via a bacteriophage, while specialized transduction transfers a restricted set of genes. These two processes can be used to help treat diseases.
phenomenonA Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonA[comment] This topic relates to the important genetic phenomenon of bacterial resistance to antibiotics. Transduction is one of the methods by which bacterial populations develop drug resistance. This occurs when antibiotic resistant are transferred between bacterium.
phenomenonB The chi square test can be used to detect whether allele frequencies in populations are inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions
phenomenonB[comment] The chi square test is important because it allows us to detect whether allele frequencies are consistent with Hardy Weinberg. If the chi square test tells us that the difference between the expected and actual allele frequencies is not due to chance then we can infer that the population is not in hardy weinberg equilibrium and that the population is in some way evolving.
groupTime426 989.94

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] The chi square test can be used to statistically determine if there is a difference between the expected and actual values allele frequencies in a population. If the result of the chi square test fails to reject the null hypothesis, we can concluded that the population is not in Hardy Weinberg equillibrium and evolution is occuring.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] Determing the frequency of alleles and genotypes for sex-linked genes is different than determining the frequency of those for non-sex linked genes. The process requires manipulation of the hardy weinberg formula. This is because for example x-chromosome linked genes will occur twice and females and only once in males.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Bacterial gene exchange via the use of viruses in both generalized and specialized transduction can be used to increase genetic variation within populations. Neither types require that the two bacterial cells involved physically touch. Rather a bacteriophage transfers the genetic information between the two. In generalized transduction, any genes are transferred, whereas in specialized a specific gene sequence, such as antibiotic resistance, is transferred. Specialized transduction is commonly used in laboratory settings to produce gene or protein products.
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] Bacterial conjugation is the transfer of genetic material between bacterial cells via direct physical contact. explainConcepts[SQ001] From Hardy Weinberg and known allele frequencies, we can infer the frequencies of the genotypes. Every individual carries and X and a Y we can predict these genotype frequencies using a chi square.
explainConcepts[SQ002] If alleles are X linked then females can be either homozygous or heterozygous only have one allele on the X gene. This causes recessive X linked traits to be more common among males than females. For predicting genotypes of sex linked, males and females have to be evaluated separately. For males it is simple because genotype frequency is allele frequency. You can still use Hardy Weinberg to predict these frequencies.
explainConcepts[SQ003] General transduction is process that DNA is transferred from one bacterium to another by a virus. General transduction is random. Specialized transduction is specific DNA fragments. Specialized is mediated by lysogenic phases.
phenomenonA Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonA[comment] This is important when thinking about two individuals having kids and potential traits being passed down. There are many things that are x-linked recessive that women can be carries for and never know before they have children. Knowing these things before having kids could cut down on the number of harmful traits passed down.
phenomenonB The chi square test can be used to detect whether allele frequencies in populations are inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions
phenomenonB[comment] For Hardy Weinberg the population has to be infinitely large, so using a chi square can be more beneficial because typically populations are not going to be infinitely large in the real world. This would be a better prediction, while Hardy Weinberg is still a good estimate. There are many requirements that HW calls for that are not going to actually happen in natural populations. Using a chi square can be helpful when looking to see whether or not HW is a good prediction or not.
