Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Ideally, if all Hardy Weinberg conditions are met, a population's alleles will exist in equilibrium. A chi square test can determine if these conditions are violated, since a small deviation from allele frequency can be attributed to chance, and "a small" deviation is clearly defined in chi squared analysis.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Using the Hardy Weinberg equation, one can determine the frequency of an allele if given the frequency of the expressed phenotype. Since the alleles follow a binomial squared, the two-variable equation can be used to find the frequency of the individual alleles.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Transduction is the process in which DNA is transferred to another bacteria via a virus. Generalized transduction involves any bacterial gene being transferred, where specialized transduction involves a specific set of genes being transferred, rather than any general gene.
phenomenonA The chi square test can be used to detect whether allele frequencies in populations are inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions
phenomenonA[comment] Random mating is related to Hardy Weinberg equilibrium. If mating is selective, certain alleles will be favored (those that increase the organism's fitness). This is the base of natural selection, which in time leads to evolution of a population.
phenomenonB The chi square test can be used to detect whether allele frequencies in populations are inconsistent with Hardy Weinberg predictions
phenomenonB[comment] For Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium to be achieved, mutation must be absent. This is always due to chance, since mutation is a random change in DNA. Mutation is the source of allele creation, which can lead to certain alleles being favored.

Also, given the frequency of the alleles, one can determine the expected homozygous dominant+recessive and heterozygous percent of a population.

phenomenonB Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonB[comment] If alleles are X-linked, females may be homozygous or heterozygous, but males carry only a single allele for each X-linked locus. For X-linked alleles in females, the H-W frequencies are the same as those for autosomal loci. In males, however, the frequencies of the genotypes will be p and q, the same as the frequencies of the alleles in the population. For this reason, recessive X-linked traits are more frequent among males than among females.
groupTime426 2356.36

Group: Self-Assessment of Understanding

knowlegeBasis[SQ001] The H-W law can be used a s null model to which the genetic structure of any particular population can be compared. If the observed genetic structure does not match the expected structure based on the law we can begin to ask which of the assumptions are being violated. To determine whether the genotypes of a population are in H-W proportions, we first compute p and q from the observed frequencies of the genotypes. Allelic frequencies may be calculated in either of two ways: from the observed numbers of different genotypes at a particular locus, or from the genotypic frequencies. First, we can calculate the allelic frequencies directly from the numbers of genotypes. In this method, we count the number of alleles of one type at a particular locus and divide it by the total number of alleles at that locus in the population.
knowlegeBasis[SQ002] The alleles are X-linked and the sexes differ in allelic frequency, the equilibrium frequencies are approached over several generations. This is because males receive their X chromosomes from their mothers only, while females receive an X chromosome from both the mother and the father. Consequently the frequency of an X-linked allele in males will be the same as the frequency of that allele in their mothers, whereas the frequency in females will be the average of that in mothers and fathers.
knowlegeBasis[SQ003] Generalized transduction -- all regions of chromosome transduced, only chromosomal DNA (i.e., no phage DNA) in transducing particles [2 points] Specialized transduction -- only specific regions of chromosome located near attachment site are transduced, transducing particles carry both chromosomal DNA and phage DNA
knowlegeBasis[SQ004] A high-frequency recombination cell (Hfr cell) (also called an Hfr strain) is a bacterium with a conjugative plasmid (often the F-factor) integrated into its genomic DNA.

explainConcepts[SQ002] When random mating occurs within a population, the equilibrium genotypic frequencies are reached in one generation. explainConcepts[SQ003] Generalized transduction is the process by which any bacterial gene may be transferred to another bacterium via a bacteriophage, and only carries bacterial DNA, No viral DNA is included. Specialized transduction is the process by which a restricted set of bacterial genes is transferred to another bacterium. The donor genes transfer really depends on the location depends on where the bacteriophage genome is located within the chromosome.

groupTime425 31.96

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The chi square test is used to determine whether there is a significant difference between the number of actual and expected genotypes. Using the chi square test tells you the probability of arriving at the differences found in the experiment by chance alone. The lower the probability generated by the test, the greater the likelihood that the difference you see between the observed and expected result is actually the result of a violation of one of the five conditions of the Hardy Weinberg rules.
explainConcepts[SQ002] When determining allele frequencies,m male and females have to be calculated separately. Males have only one copy of sex linked genes so for males, the genotype frequency equals the allele frequency. On the other hand, female sex linked genes can be determined like any other inherited autosomal trait because they have two copies. After the p and q from the hardy weinberg is calculated from the males, this information can be used to determine the frequenies present in females who are carriers and who are non carriers.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Generalized transduction is when a piece of host DNA gets packaged by mistake instead of the phage DNA. This results in a phage delivering only bacterial DNA to the next host. The DNA then recombines homologously, replacing the host allele. Specialized transduction occurs when a lysogenic prophage recombines itself out of the genome by site specific recombination and mistakenly includes a piece of bacterial DNA. The resulting phage can infect cells to produce lysogens with a second copy of the allele they had packaged, attached to the phage DNA.
phenomenonA Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonA[comment] Red green colorblindness is a sex linked trait in humans. In males, the genotype and the phenotypic ratios are equal. Therefore, if out of 100 men, ten were colorblind, p=.9 and q=.1 in the Hardy Weinberg equation because each male has only one allele for this gene.
phenomenonB Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonB[comment] Lateral gene transfer has recently become an interest of study because as gene mapping has become easier, the prevalence of gene transfer has become more aware. There are many studies that look into the diagnosis of cancer and the relation that it may have with bacterial gene transfer. Noninherited bacterial DNA transfer into chromosomes in human somatic cells could induce mutations leading to cancer or autoimmune diseases in a manner analogous to mobile elements and viral integrations.
groupTime426 1982.53

explainConcepts[SQ001] The Chi Square Test is a statistical tool to reject a null hypothesis. It can be applied to analyze the allele frequencies within a population. The observed in this case are actual frequencies while expected are the Hardy Weinberg predictions.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Sex linked genes have a different pattern of inheritance compared to autosomal genes. For males, the Hardy Weinberg equation is simply p + q = 1 while females remain the same.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Viruses are able to uptake bacterial DNA, reproduce, and infect new cells. It is possible to then inject the new DNA, containing virus and Bacterial DNA, into a different bacterial cell, generating genetic diversity.

phenomenonB[comment] A population can be determined to not be in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium, suggesting one or more the assumptions are not true. For instance, an allele is being selected for.

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] Based on the value of chi square test, if the actual and expected values are not significantly different, the null hypothesis is not rejected, we can conclude that the population is at Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium. on the other hand, if the actual values and expected are significant different, the null hypothesis is reject, therefore, the population is not at Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium
explainConcepts[SQ002] the same principles can be applied to sex-linked traits if males and females are treated separately. males have only one copy of sex-linked gene so for male: genotype frequencies= allele frequency.
explainConcepts[SQ003] the fragment of bacterial DNA involved in a transduction event maybe large enough to include several genes.
phenomenonA Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonA[comment] generalized transduction occurs when the enzyme that normally cuts the concatamer cuts the host chromosome instead. the viral capsids cannot distinguish viral DNA from host DNA. thus, once the initial cut is made, the empty capsids are filled with host chromosomal DNA instant of viral DNA Specialized transduction occurs when the enzyme that cuts the viral DNA out of the host chromosome makes a mistake and cuts in the wrong place, removing some, but not at all, of the viral genes. specialized transducing virus can pick yp gene only on either side of the site where the virus integrates into the bacterial chromosome.
phenomenonB Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonB[comment] generalized transduction is usually mediated by certain lytic viruses. a lytic virus is one that normally infects a host cell and redirects the resources of the host away from its own cellular replication toward viral replication and the eventual lysis, or breaking open, of the bacterial cell. Specialized transduction results in the movement of only specific genes. the viruses that carry out specialized transduction are called lysosgenic virus. they have a mechanism for replication that is different from that of generalized transduction, for they integrate their DNA directly into the chromosome of its host's genome. each tome the host chromosome is duplicated, so is the integrated viral DNA

Group: Explain Concepts & Link to Phenomena

explainConcepts[SQ001] The chi square test is used as a statistical analysis for determining if the null hypothesis is a good fit for the data gathered. This test can be used to examine the allele frequencies and ratios within a population and determine if they match up close enough to be considered in Hardy Weinberg equilibrium to measure the inconsistencies.
explainConcepts[SQ002] Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes is important because it is easy to predict very accurately and it allows geneticists and students to easily track genotypes that result in genetic disorders. For example, colorblindness is a sex linked disorder that is often used to teach how alleles and genotypes that use the sex linked mode of inheritance can be tracked.
explainConcepts[SQ003] Transduction is the process of bacterial recombination through the mediation of bacteriophages. This process involves a virus compromising a bacterium and combining DNA with the host. Then the virus leaves the host either on its own or by causing the host cell to lyse. The virus then moves on does the same to a different cell but takes some of the DNA from the first cell along with it and continues to repeat the process. This gives the bacteria genetic diversity.
phenomenonA Determining the frequency of alleles and genotypes with sex linked genes.
phenomenonA[comment] The determining of allele and genotype frequency through sex linked genes is a topic I find particularly interesting. Mostly, I'm interested in sex linked genes because they make it possible to track genetic diseases like colorblindness which is find interesting because colorblindness runs in my family.
phenomenonB Bacterial gene exchange may be mediated by viruses by either generalized transduction or specialized transduction.
phenomenonB[comment] The transduction of genes through bacteriophages is a genetic phenomenon that I'm particularly interested in. The idea that viruses which normally have a negative connotation have the ability to provide bacteria with genetic diversity is extremely interesting.
